1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,000
The event is over.

2
00:00:07,300 --> 00:00:09,300
Every session is ENDED.

3
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:12,225
The last speaker has left the stage.

4
00:00:12,525 --> 00:00:17,025
Now comes the part that production teams usually dread — the debrief.

5
00:00:17,325 --> 00:00:19,325
Which sessions ran late?

6
00:00:19,625 --> 00:00:21,625
By how much?

7
00:00:21,925 --> 00:00:23,925
Who triggered what, and when?

8
00:00:24,225 --> 00:00:27,600
If something went wrong at two-thirty, what exactly happened?

9
00:00:27,900 --> 00:00:31,650
CueDeck has been recording every single action throughout the day

10
00:00:31,950 --> 00:00:34,200
— every state change, every delay,

11
00:00:34,500 --> 00:00:36,500
every broadcast, every actor.

12
00:00:36,800 --> 00:00:39,800
That data doesn't disappear when the event ends.

13
00:00:40,100 --> 00:00:43,475
In this episode we're going to look at where

14
00:00:43,775 --> 00:00:46,025
it lives, how to read it,

15
00:00:46,325 --> 00:00:50,075
and how to turn it into a document you can

16
00:00:50,375 --> 00:00:52,375
actually send to a client.

17
00:00:52,675 --> 00:00:56,425
The event log is the audit trail for everything that

18
00:00:56,725 --> 00:00:58,725
happened during the day.

19
00:00:59,025 --> 00:01:02,025
It lives in the `leod_event_log` table in Supabase,

20
00:01:02,325 --> 00:01:07,200
and CueDeck surfaces it right here in the console — no SQL required.

21
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:09,750
Every row is a state transition.

22
00:01:10,050 --> 00:01:13,050
Time it happened, the session it applies to,

23
00:01:13,350 --> 00:01:16,350
what the transition was — PLANNED to READY,

24
00:01:16,650 --> 00:01:19,275
READY to LIVE, LIVE to ENDED —

25
00:01:19,575 --> 00:01:21,575
and which operator triggered it.

26
00:01:21,875 --> 00:01:23,875
Name and role, both recorded.

27
00:01:24,175 --> 00:01:26,175
Let me scroll through this.

28
00:01:26,475 --> 00:01:29,850
You can see exactly how Session 2 played out.

29
00:01:30,150 --> 00:01:32,775
Ready at nine-oh-two, speaker called at nine-oh-four,

30
00:01:33,075 --> 00:01:35,075
went live at nine-oh-five.

31
00:01:35,375 --> 00:01:39,875
That's a three-minute window from ready to live — tighter than average.

32
00:01:40,175 --> 00:01:42,175
Good execution.

33
00:01:42,475 --> 00:01:44,475
Now look further down.

34
00:01:44,775 --> 00:01:46,775
Here's the delay at ten-forty-seven.

35
00:01:47,075 --> 00:01:49,075
The panel was running long.

36
00:01:49,375 --> 00:01:53,875
Five minutes applied, cascade fired to every subsequent session in that room.

37
00:01:54,175 --> 00:01:57,175
The log captured exactly when it happened and

38
00:01:57,475 --> 00:01:59,475
who made the call.

39
00:01:59,775 --> 00:02:03,525
If a client asks 'why did the afternoon session start

40
00:02:03,825 --> 00:02:06,450
twelve minutes late,' this is your answer.

41
00:02:06,750 --> 00:02:09,375
You can point to a specific row,

42
00:02:09,675 --> 00:02:12,300
a specific time, and a specific person.

43
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:14,600
That's the accountability layer.

44
00:02:14,900 --> 00:02:18,650
Under the hood the log table has everything you'd want

45
00:02:18,950 --> 00:02:20,950
for a proper audit trail.

46
00:02:21,250 --> 00:02:23,875
Every row has the session ID and

47
00:02:24,175 --> 00:02:27,175
title — so you can filter by session.

48
00:02:27,475 --> 00:02:30,850
The `from_status` and `to_status` columns capture the full transition,

49
00:02:31,150 --> 00:02:33,150
not just the destination.

50
00:02:33,450 --> 00:02:36,075
The actor fields record who triggered it:

51
00:02:36,375 --> 00:02:39,375
their ID, their role, and their display name.

52
00:02:39,675 --> 00:02:42,300
And `created_at` is a full timezone-aware timestamp.

53
00:02:42,600 --> 00:02:44,850
There's also a notes column —

54
00:02:45,150 --> 00:02:48,900
that's populated when a broadcast goes out alongside a state

55
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:52,950
change, or when the Incident Advisor logs a flagged event.

56
00:02:53,250 --> 00:02:57,000
You'll never need to dig this deep for a normal

57
00:02:57,300 --> 00:03:00,300
debrief — CueDeck surfaces it in the console.

58
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:03,600
But when a client wants a formal record,

59
00:03:03,900 --> 00:03:06,150
or when something went wrong and

60
00:03:06,450 --> 00:03:09,450
you need the raw data, it's all here.

61
00:03:09,750 --> 00:03:13,125
Now let's connect the log to the client-facing output.

62
00:03:13,425 --> 00:03:17,175
The Report Generator — which we covered in Episode 13

63
00:03:17,475 --> 00:03:20,100
— pulls all of this data and

64
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:23,775
presents it in a format you can actually send.

65
00:03:24,075 --> 00:03:27,075
The Sessions tab is where the variance lives.

66
00:03:27,375 --> 00:03:31,125
Every session, side by side: planned start time from your

67
00:03:31,425 --> 00:03:34,800
original programme, actual start time from the event log,

68
00:03:35,100 --> 00:03:37,100
and the delta in minutes.

69
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:39,400
Positive numbers mean late.

70
00:03:39,700 --> 00:03:42,325
Negative means you were ahead of schedule.

71
00:03:42,625 --> 00:03:44,625
Look at the colour coding.

72
00:03:44,925 --> 00:03:48,300
Green rows started on time or within a minute.

73
00:03:48,600 --> 00:03:53,100
Orange sessions drifted two to four minutes late — normal production variance.

74
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:57,150
The red rows are where you had real schedule pressure.

75
00:03:57,450 --> 00:04:01,200
In this example, the afternoon keynote started seven minutes late

76
00:04:01,500 --> 00:04:04,875
— that's the one where the delay cascade fired.

77
00:04:05,175 --> 00:04:08,925
The log tells you why: the panel before it ran

78
00:04:09,225 --> 00:04:11,850
over, the delay was applied at ten-forty-seven,

79
00:04:12,150 --> 00:04:14,150
and it rolled downstream.

80
00:04:14,450 --> 00:04:18,575
This is not a story you have to reconstruct from notes.

81
00:04:18,875 --> 00:04:21,500
It's already here, timestamped to the second.

82
00:04:21,800 --> 00:04:24,800
For clients who want a full spreadsheet —

83
00:04:25,100 --> 00:04:27,725
or for your own production archive —

84
00:04:28,025 --> 00:04:31,025
there's a SQL export query included with CueDeck.

85
00:04:31,325 --> 00:04:33,950
Paste this into the Supabase SQL Editor,

86
00:04:34,250 --> 00:04:38,750
replace the event ID placeholder with your event's UUID, and run it.

87
00:04:39,050 --> 00:04:42,800
What you get back is one row per session with

88
00:04:43,100 --> 00:04:45,350
every timing field: planned start and

89
00:04:45,650 --> 00:04:49,025
end, scheduled start and end after any delay cascade,

90
00:04:49,325 --> 00:04:52,325
actual start and end from the live run,

91
00:04:52,625 --> 00:04:57,125
and the variance in minutes against both the planned and scheduled times.

92
00:04:57,425 --> 00:05:00,050
It also includes the production flags —

93
00:05:00,350 --> 00:05:04,100
speaker arrived, mic type, recording on or off, streaming, interpretation.

94
00:05:04,400 --> 00:05:08,150
Everything that was set on the session record comes through.

95
00:05:08,450 --> 00:05:12,200
Hit Export CSV and you have a spreadsheet you can

96
00:05:12,500 --> 00:05:16,250
open in Excel or Google Sheets in about three seconds.

97
00:05:16,550 --> 00:05:19,925
Filter it, sort it by variance, chart the deltas.

98
00:05:20,225 --> 00:05:22,475
That's your post-event data asset —

99
00:05:22,775 --> 00:05:25,775
it follows every event you run on CueDeck.

100
00:05:26,075 --> 00:05:29,450
Four things this gets you in the real world.

101
00:05:29,750 --> 00:05:31,750
First, client debrief.

102
00:05:32,050 --> 00:05:35,800
Within an hour of the event ending you can send

103
00:05:36,100 --> 00:05:39,850
a professional written summary — generated by the Report Generator

104
00:05:40,150 --> 00:05:43,525
— with the variance data attached as a CSV.

105
00:05:43,825 --> 00:05:46,075
That turnaround time is a differentiator.

106
00:05:46,375 --> 00:05:48,375
Second, billing justification.

107
00:05:48,675 --> 00:05:52,050
If you're billing for overtime on a specific room,

108
00:05:52,350 --> 00:05:54,350
the timestamps are your evidence.

109
00:05:54,650 --> 00:05:58,025
You went live at nine-oh-five, you wrapped at eighteen-forty-two.

110
00:05:58,325 --> 00:06:00,950
That's the billable day, in the database.

111
00:06:01,250 --> 00:06:03,250
Third, incident accountability.

112
00:06:03,550 --> 00:06:05,800
If something went wrong at fourteen-thirty-two,

113
00:06:06,100 --> 00:06:09,475
you have a log entry with the exact time,

114
00:06:09,775 --> 00:06:13,525
the operator who responded, and the system that was affected.

115
00:06:13,825 --> 00:06:18,325
No 'I think it was around half two' — it was fourteen-thirty-two.

116
00:06:18,625 --> 00:06:20,625
And fourth, continuous improvement.

117
00:06:20,925 --> 00:06:22,925
Run three events.

118
00:06:23,225 --> 00:06:25,225
Export the variance CSVs.

119
00:06:25,525 --> 00:06:28,150
Plot the average delay per session type.

120
00:06:28,450 --> 00:06:32,200
You'll know within two events whether your keynotes consistently run

121
00:06:32,500 --> 00:06:35,125
long, whether your breaks are too short,

122
00:06:35,425 --> 00:06:38,050
and where to add buffer next year.

123
00:06:38,350 --> 00:06:43,225
That kind of institutional knowledge used to live in a production manager's head.

124
00:06:43,525 --> 00:06:45,525
Now it's in a table.

125
00:06:45,825 --> 00:06:50,700
The event log and the post-event report are the accountability layer in CueDeck.

126
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:54,000
Every transition is stored, every actor is identified,

127
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:56,550
every minute of variance is measured.

128
00:06:56,850 --> 00:06:59,100
Used together — the in-console log,

129
00:06:59,400 --> 00:07:02,775
the AI Report Generator, and the SQL export —

130
00:07:03,075 --> 00:07:06,825
you have everything you need to close out an event

131
00:07:07,125 --> 00:07:09,375
professionally and improve the next one.

132
00:07:09,675 --> 00:07:13,425
In the next episode we're going deep on something that

133
00:07:13,725 --> 00:07:17,475
changes how fast you can work inside the console —

134
00:07:17,775 --> 00:07:20,025
keyboard shortcuts and the command palette.

135
00:07:20,325 --> 00:07:24,075
If you've ever wished you could trigger a session transition

136
00:07:24,375 --> 00:07:28,125
without taking your eyes off the stage, that's the episode.

137
00:07:28,425 --> 00:07:30,425
See you there.
